{
  "text": "In light of the above, we proceed to state a concrete discrepancy between the analysis and synthesis models: The synthesis model defines graph signals as linear combinations of (perturbed) piecewise quadratic polynomials, encompassing piecewise linear and piecewise constant signals for suitable coefficient choices. This signifies a more comprehensive model containing different orders of smoothness and localization of the solution spaces, while the analysis model constitutes a structured instance thereof which defines signals that are sparse with respect to L, up to a shift by N (L). For sufficiently banded GS, the 'perturbed' quadratic (L \u2020 )j can further be annihilated by L 2 , whose rows, by extension, factor 4 vanishing moments, as per (Lemma 3.1, [CITATION_1] ).",
  "citation_candidates": [
